      "sections": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Traffic Engineering",
          "table": {
            "header": ["SUB-TOPIC", "SHORT DESCRIPTION / NOTES", "EXTRA"],
            "rows": [
              [
                "TRAFFIC ENGINEERING DEFINITION",
                "Branch of transportation engineering for planning, design, operation & control of traffic so people and goods move safely and efficiently.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "TRAFFIC CHARACTERISTICS",
                "**Road users:** Drivers, pedestrians, cyclists, animals.\nVehicle traits: Length, width, weight, acceleration, braking, max speed.\nTraffic stream: Flow (q), Speed (v), Density (k) related by q = k × v (q in veh/hr, v in km/hr, k in veh/km).",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "TRAFFIC VOLUME STUDY",
                "Counts vehicles crossing a point/section in specified time.\nUnits: veh/hr, veh/day.\nADT & AADT used for design, capacity, signal timings, planning.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "SPEED STUDIES",
                "Spot speed; Time-mean speed (arithmetic mean of spot speeds); Space-mean speed (harmonic mean; correct travel time); 85th percentile speed; Running vs Journey speed.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "PARKING STUDIES",
                "Inventory, accumulation, duration, turnover. Types: On-street (parallel, angle, perpendicular), Off-street (lots, garages).",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "ACCIDENT STUDIES",
                "Causes: Human error, road geometry, vehicle condition, weather, lighting. Data: location, time, vehicles, severity, road condition. Uses: black spots, countermeasures.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "TRAFFIC CONTROL DEVICES",
                "Signs (Regulatory/Warning/Informational), Signals (fixed-time/actuated/coordinated), Markings (longitudinal/transverse/hazard). Nepal: DoR manuals first; IRC if DoR is silent.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "HIGHWAY CAPACITY",
                "C = V / PHF. Typical ideal ≈ 2000 veh/hr/lane under good conditions.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "STREET LIGHTING",
                "Design: average illuminance (30–50 lux main roads), uniformity, glare control, pole height & spacing.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "INTERSECTION DESIGN",
                "Design junctions for safety & flow. Types: At-grade (T, Y, cross), Grade-separated (flyovers/underpasses). Channelization. Rotary/Roundabout reduces conflict points. Design elements: entry/exit radius, entry angle, flare, weaving length.",
                ""
              ]
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "formulas",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Important Formulas (quick reference)",
          "items": [
            { "name": "Flow–Speed–Density", "expr": "q = k × v" },
            { "name": "AADT", "expr": "AADT = Total yearly traffic / 365" },
            { "name": "Time-mean speed (Vt)", "expr": "Vt = (ΣVi) / n" },
            { "name": "Space-mean speed (Vs)", "expr": "Vs = n / Σ(1/Vi)" },
            { "name": "Relationship", "expr": "Vt ≥ Vs" },
            { "name": "Stopping Sight Distance (SSD)", "expr": "SSD = 0.278 V t + V² / (254 f)" },
            { "name": "Highway capacity (basic)", "expr": "C = V / PHF" },
            { "name": "Peak Hour Factor (PHF)", "expr": "PHF = V60 / (4 × V15)" },
            {
              "name": "Parking Index (%)",
              "expr": "Parking Index = (Vehicles parked / Total parking spaces) × 100"
            },
            {
              "name": "Accident rate (per million vehicle-km)",
              "expr": "Accident rate = (No. of accidents × 10^6) / (AADT × Length(km) × 365)"
            },
            { "name": "Approx. Weaving length (empirical)", "expr": "L ≈ 2.7 (W + 3.5) + V/2" }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "notes",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Important Points / Exam Tips (short & sharp)",
          "content": "**Key Points:**\n- Always state units (km/h, veh/hr, veh/km).\n- For SSD use reaction time `t = 2.5 s` (conservative) or `2.0 s` (urban) depending on code.\n- Use *85th percentile speed* to justify speed limits.\n- For capacity problems mention __lane width__, __lateral clearance__, __heavy vehicle %__ as adjustment factors.\n- **Black-spot remedies:** signage, speed calming, improved lighting, channelization.\n- For Nepal code, cite DoR / Nepal road manuals; refer to IRC where DoR is silent."
        },
